It also seems that the European accounts seem to have more of a tendency to have few followers and few tweets -- maybe this suggests that Twitter is less widely-used in their countries?

S-task08.prompt: Among all people who have interacted with both Jeffrey and Robert, who has the most followers?

answer.value:
The cluster has more people than institutions, and are mostly made up of NA and EU users. It has a very high average account age and follower counts, but tweets are more variable.

There are is a section of people who have only interacted with Jeffrey, but most of the people he interacted with are from outside of the cluster. Jeffrey also has the highest follower count.

Robert also has a high number of accounts that he interacted with, but they are split between the cluster and outside of it.

Krist has the most tweets. Lynn has the oldest account. But both of these users have very few interactions within the network, despite having high numbers in all fields (followers, tweets, account age).

When sorted by continent, EU users form almost the outline of a cube through their interactions.

answer.value: I am astonished by how many interactions does every person on this network have with each other. It feels incredibly interconnected. Also, there are some people who are are extremely social, like robert and alex, while others only interact with only one or two people. I would expect institutions to have more interactions overall, after all, they are formed by a wide variety of people who have different networks. And finally, it suprises me the fact that almost everyone on this network is active in twitter and have hundreds of followers, interactions, likes and tweets.

overallFeedback.overall: Was a quite fairly interesting data ''game'', useful for teaching children in primary school etc. how strong social media is and the influence certain people can have. Basically you’re a node in a network. Of course that’s even more true now that we have social media. You’ll know a thousand people at least over the course of your life, and they’ll know a thousand people each, and that puts you one person away from a million, and two persons away from a billion. And so that’s how you’re connected, and the things you do is like dropping a stone in a pond. The ripples move outward, and they affect things in ways that you can’t fully comprehend.

answer.value:
It is surprising the the network has an obvious 'nucleus' of contributors, and then such an array of outliers. For example, Helwig only interacts with Thomas. Unsurprisingly those outliers have the fewest followers and often tweets. 

However looking towards the centre of the diagram - where you see the most nodes, you would expect to see a correlation between tweets and follows (e.g. like Robert), but that isn't always the case. Tamara, MViews and EEyes have lots of tweets but not a correspondingly high number of followers. 

Most users tend to be from North America or Europe - there also tend to be geographical clusters. Maybe time difference and real-time interactions still have a bearing in the digital age?

It also appears institutions have fewer followers overall than people. Interesting!
